1
00:00:17,142 --> 00:00:19,645
[footsteps approaching]

2
00:00:44,044 --> 00:00:46,547
[footsteps continue]

3
00:01:06,650 --> 00:01:09,152
[footsteps continue]

4
00:01:25,335 --> 00:01:27,838
[footsteps continue]

5
00:01:29,631 --> 00:01:31,633
[police radio chatter]

6
00:01:37,931 --> 00:01:38,932
[siren blares]

7
00:01:46,648 --> 00:01:48,108
[radio chatter continues]

8
00:01:53,906 --> 00:01:56,466
[Rachel] I've been waiting for hours.
She's been there all night.

9
00:01:56,491 --> 00:01:58,785
Look out the window.
The sun is fucking coming up.

10
00:01:58,869 --> 00:02:00,889
[nurse] I'm sorry.
You're gonna need to take a seat.

11
00:02:00,913 --> 00:02:02,915
Well, where's the doctor?
Where's the doctor?

12
00:02:02,998 --> 00:02:05,685
- I wanna talk to him. Where's the doctor?
- [nurse] She's on her way.

13
00:02:05,709 --> 00:02:08,044
[Rachel] Just let me see
my daughter Sharon.

14
00:02:08,127 --> 00:02:10,047
I'd like to actually get
some answers, okay?

15
00:02:10,130 --> 00:02:12,066
[nurse] Please take a seat.
We'll be able to help you soon.

16
00:02:12,090 --> 00:02:15,260
[Rachel] Who's your supervisor?
This is not okay.

17
00:02:15,344 --> 00:02:17,572
- [nurse] He'll be here soon.
- [Rachel] I just wanna see her.

18
00:02:17,596 --> 00:02:20,408
- [nurse] Ma'am, I understand.
- [Rachel] Yeah, yeah, yeah. Unbelievable.

19
00:02:20,432 --> 00:02:22,142
Sir, this is a restricted area.

20
00:02:38,116 --> 00:02:39,117
[grunts]

21
00:02:42,538 --> 00:02:43,872
Are you serious right now?

22
00:02:45,415 --> 00:02:48,460
There's a hundred other
fucking chairs here. Pick one.

23
00:02:49,378 --> 00:02:50,504
I'm already in this one.

24
00:02:51,505 --> 00:02:52,798
[scoffs]

25
00:02:52,881 --> 00:02:56,301
Just go away.
I can't deal with whatever this is.

26
00:02:56,385 --> 00:02:57,511
No, I understand.

27
00:02:59,054 --> 00:03:00,180
Waiting's no fun.

28
00:03:01,431 --> 00:03:04,935
Nurses don't tell you nothing, and the doctors don't do their rounds till 7:00.

29
00:03:06,728 --> 00:03:07,729
Oh, fuck.

30
00:03:11,942 --> 00:03:13,110
Who you waiting for?

31
00:03:16,238 --> 00:03:17,781
- My daughter.
- Oh.

32
00:03:19,533 --> 00:03:20,659
Why is she here?

33
00:03:26,582 --> 00:03:28,125
The critical cases get seen to first.

34
00:03:28,208 --> 00:03:31,086
So, if your daughter needs a specialist,
you'll be waiting here a while.

35
00:03:32,421 --> 00:03:33,463
You a doctor?

36
00:03:33,547 --> 00:03:42,556
No, I, um… [clicks tongue] Been on this side of it before.

37
00:03:44,099 --> 00:03:48,979
It's, um… It's hard not knowing.

38
00:03:50,314 --> 00:03:53,233
She was on the beach.
What the fuck was she doing on the beach?

39
00:03:55,068 --> 00:03:56,195
Your daughter was?

40
00:03:56,987 --> 00:03:58,322
That's what the cops said.

41
00:03:59,281 --> 00:04:01,617
She could've walked
that shitty dog anywhere.

42
00:04:01,700 --> 00:04:04,453
It's the middle of the night. And what?
She wants to go for a swim?

43
00:04:04,536 --> 00:04:05,537
[breathes shakily]

44
00:04:06,205 --> 00:04:08,332
Well, maybe she just wanted it to herself.

45
00:04:09,708 --> 00:04:10,876
You know, the beach.

46
00:04:12,377 --> 00:04:13,962
Why the fuck would she want that?

47
00:04:14,463 --> 00:04:16,673
Someone cuts her open,
just leaves her there.

48
00:04:17,341 --> 00:04:18,341
I'm sorry.

49
00:04:18,841 --> 00:04:20,594
Don't be sorry. She's not dying.

50
00:04:21,595 --> 00:04:23,639
Hey, hey, hey! Don't walk away from me.

51
00:04:23,722 --> 00:04:25,766
Where's the doctor?
Okay. Where's the doctor?

52
00:04:25,849 --> 00:04:28,477
- [nurse] She's on her way...
- [Rachel] She's on her way?

53
00:04:28,560 --> 00:04:30,497
- You said that hours ago.
- [nurse] You need to wait for her.

54
00:04:30,521 --> 00:04:33,232
- [Rachel] Where's the doctor?
- [nurse] I know. Like I said...

55
00:04:33,315 --> 00:04:36,527
[Rachel] I am not moving
until the doctor comes here.

56
00:04:36,610 --> 00:04:39,029
I am not moving. I mean, what is going on?

57
00:04:40,864 --> 00:04:43,617
[Rachel] I've been waiting for five hours.
When is her shift done?

58
00:05:31,999 --> 00:05:33,834
[Harper] How'd you get here, Sharon?

59
00:05:34,501 --> 00:05:36,712
[nurse 2] Hey. You can't be in here.

60
00:05:38,046 --> 00:05:40,174
- [heart rate monitor beeping]
- Wrong room. Sorry.

61
00:05:42,843 --> 00:05:45,012
[nurse 2] Come on. Let's go, now!

62
00:06:41,026 --> 00:06:44,321
[reporter] I'm waiting on
the '87 Bulls stats. It's under Royko.

63
00:06:53,330 --> 00:06:55,791
One was found in Bronzeville,
the other one in Englewood.

64
00:06:55,874 --> 00:06:57,459
The furthest out was Berwyn.

65
00:06:57,543 --> 00:06:58,812
[Lakshmi] There's seven women here.

66
00:06:58,836 --> 00:07:00,838
Over a 20-year spread.

67
00:07:00,921 --> 00:07:02,548
And there's probably more.

68
00:07:02,631 --> 00:07:04,216
Your source can't be CPD.

69
00:07:04,299 --> 00:07:06,343
I haven't run any of this by them yet.

70
00:07:06,426 --> 00:07:07,845
Then how can you be so sure?

71
00:07:10,472 --> 00:07:14,268
Someone had been calling Julia
for weeks before her murder.

72
00:07:14,351 --> 00:07:15,644
She recorded him.

73
00:07:17,312 --> 00:07:19,231
- I got the tapes. And now...
- [Bertie] Wait.

74
00:07:19,314 --> 00:07:21,191
Does the DA know you have them?

75
00:07:21,275 --> 00:07:23,193
[stammers]
We're just stealing evidence now?

76
00:07:23,277 --> 00:07:26,780
And my source recognized the voice
on Julia's recordings.

77
00:07:27,447 --> 00:07:29,575
It's the same man who attacked her.

78
00:07:30,075 --> 00:07:32,077
[Bertie]
Uh, wait, your source is a victim?

79
00:07:32,160 --> 00:07:33,912
She's the one who brought the story to me.

80
00:07:33,996 --> 00:07:37,165
And she's refusing to be featured.
Even if we keep her anonymous.

81
00:07:37,249 --> 00:07:39,918
Abby, I don't need a survivor.

82
00:07:40,919 --> 00:07:44,715
I'll do the legwork. I'll connect
the women. And I'll confirm what we have.

83
00:07:44,798 --> 00:07:46,401
[reporter] Let me see that file.
Let me see.

84
00:07:46,425 --> 00:07:49,094
- Look at what he's gotten away with.
- [reporter] I got it.

85
00:07:49,178 --> 00:07:51,096
[Abby] Wrap up the flood.
Help Dan on this.

86
00:07:51,180 --> 00:07:52,574
I can cover Daley's conference for you.

87
00:07:52,598 --> 00:07:54,701
[Bertie] No.
We don't need a presence there right now.

88
00:07:54,725 --> 00:07:58,478
[reporter 2] If we don't go, he'll notice,
and he'll punish us for it later.

89
00:08:02,733 --> 00:08:03,817
[sighs]

90
00:08:03,901 --> 00:08:04,902
[clicks tongue]

91
00:08:08,989 --> 00:08:11,366
[Kirby] Here.
I pulled background on Summer Francis.

92
00:08:12,993 --> 00:08:15,662
How'd it go?
Geez, they beat you up in there?

93
00:08:15,746 --> 00:08:17,414
All good. More work to do.

94
00:08:18,290 --> 00:08:21,001
Okay, so we covered Summer's murder.
We did a feature.

95
00:08:21,084 --> 00:08:24,588
Marcus pulled the negatives, and he found a shot of what was inside Summer.

96
00:08:26,798 --> 00:08:28,958
- [Dan] You have any other ones?
- [Kirby] This was it.

97
00:08:31,470 --> 00:08:33,096
You put Marcus up to this morning?

98
00:08:33,847 --> 00:08:35,640
- Up to what?
- He came to the meeting.

99
00:08:37,851 --> 00:08:39,686
[scoffs] You two just never talk?

100
00:08:41,188 --> 00:08:42,188
Look.

101
00:08:42,731 --> 00:08:46,276
This is a key to a staff locker
at the Adler Planetarium.

102
00:08:46,360 --> 00:08:49,112
A woman who works there
lost the identical one.

103
00:08:49,196 --> 00:08:50,572
When did you find all this out?

104
00:08:50,656 --> 00:08:53,283
Last night.
I called you, but you didn't pick up.

105
00:08:53,825 --> 00:08:56,912
Summer Francis died in '72.
And this woman is working there now?

106
00:08:56,995 --> 00:08:59,835
- Yeah, but she lost her key two weeks ago.
- So, it's not the same one.

107
00:09:03,877 --> 00:09:08,131
I have to cover seven murders
without the primary source.

108
00:09:08,215 --> 00:09:10,759
I can still help you.
I'll reach out to the families.

109
00:09:10,843 --> 00:09:16,032
Some woman loses her keys last week, and you're trying to connect this to a murder that happened 20 years ago.

110
00:09:16,056 --> 00:09:17,700
I don't know
how that's supposed to help me.

111
00:09:17,724 --> 00:09:22,104
You wanna help? I need someone
to pick up the Madrigal tapes.

112
00:09:22,187 --> 00:09:23,772
[breathes heavily]

113
00:09:26,316 --> 00:09:30,696
You should head over now,
'cause Warren closes up shop by 3:00.

114
00:09:43,625 --> 00:09:44,668
Fuck.

115
00:09:45,544 --> 00:09:46,879
[sighs]

116
00:09:49,173 --> 00:09:51,300
- Hey.
- Hey.

117
00:09:51,383 --> 00:09:52,943
Those Francis negatives, they work out?

118
00:09:53,844 --> 00:09:55,679
We're going in a different direction.

119
00:09:56,180 --> 00:09:59,558
It's a big story.
Probably a lot of directions it could go.

120
00:09:59,641 --> 00:10:03,353
Hmm. Is that what the meeting
was about this morning?

121
00:10:05,939 --> 00:10:07,774
You couldn't go.
I thought one of us should.

122
00:10:10,027 --> 00:10:11,236
Mmm.

123
00:10:11,904 --> 00:10:12,905
Where you headed?

124
00:10:14,114 --> 00:10:16,241
I'm going to go pick up tapes
in the South Loop.

125
00:10:16,325 --> 00:10:18,035
- The Madrigal recordings?
- Yeah. [sighs]

126
00:10:18,118 --> 00:10:19,244
I'll come with.

127
00:10:22,497 --> 00:10:24,208
Fill you in on where Abby left it.

128
00:10:26,210 --> 00:10:27,419
All right. [sighs]

129
00:10:37,930 --> 00:10:42,601
[Kirby] That key chain in the photo, you sure it couldn't have gotten mixed in from some other spread?

130
00:10:43,143 --> 00:10:46,647
I blew that up from the negative
you gave me, the one of Summer Francis.

131
00:10:48,273 --> 00:10:52,277
[conductor speaking indistinctly over PA]

132
00:10:52,361 --> 00:10:53,862
[shutter clicks]

133
00:10:53,946 --> 00:10:55,405
Hey. What are you doing?

134
00:10:55,906 --> 00:10:58,450
Trying to get the pictures
of those women out of my head.

135
00:10:58,534 --> 00:10:59,826
Replace it with something nice.

136
00:11:02,120 --> 00:11:04,560
- [shutter clicks]
- [Marcus laughing] Yeah, give me one more.

137
00:11:05,874 --> 00:11:07,000
[shutter clicks]

138
00:11:07,084 --> 00:11:09,336
There you are, my sunny bride.

139
00:11:11,839 --> 00:11:13,090
Oh, I like that one.

140
00:11:13,173 --> 00:11:14,842
I appreciate the time. Thank you.

141
00:11:15,759 --> 00:11:17,010
Was that the Lower sister?

142
00:11:17,094 --> 00:11:20,347
Did you talk to the, uh,
guy at Northwestern?

143
00:11:20,430 --> 00:11:27,479
Yeah, he said the incisions
could be religious or anti-religious, or just some bad memory connected to a cross.

144
00:11:27,563 --> 00:11:29,356
What about leaving stuff
inside the victims?

145
00:11:29,439 --> 00:11:30,440
What does that mean?

146
00:11:30,524 --> 00:11:33,694
He doesn't have enough context,
and we can't quote him on any of this.

147
00:11:33,777 --> 00:11:38,031
Hey, the detective who worked
Catherine Moore's case, she's retired, but she's open to helping us.

148
00:11:38,115 --> 00:11:40,677
- She'll make a few calls.
- But will she share her original notes?

149
00:11:40,701 --> 00:11:42,327
I can ask. She'll say no.

150
00:11:43,036 --> 00:11:44,514
- Matty from the Tribune called.
- Who?

151
00:11:44,538 --> 00:11:46,164
Matty Spears, their new city editor.

152
00:11:46,248 --> 00:11:48,041
He heard you stopped by
the property locker.

153
00:11:48,625 --> 00:11:49,918
[Lakshmi] How'd they get that?

154
00:11:51,420 --> 00:11:53,964
Did you give a retired detective
the other women's names?

155
00:11:55,549 --> 00:11:56,550
Fuck.

156
00:11:57,301 --> 00:11:59,501
[Abby] So, they have all the same victims
you turned up.

157
00:12:02,639 --> 00:12:03,807
We could print tonight.

158
00:12:07,227 --> 00:12:10,522
Listen… just as a holding piece.

159
00:12:11,023 --> 00:12:14,193
Two paragraphs for each victim,
and then we tease there's more to come.

160
00:12:14,276 --> 00:12:16,904
Without your source,
it reads like random murders.

161
00:12:16,987 --> 00:12:18,488
There's other ways to link 'em.

162
00:12:19,198 --> 00:12:23,174
How he picked the women, what they have in common, the objects that he left inside of them.

163
00:12:23,702 --> 00:12:24,862
I can find those connections.

164
00:12:26,246 --> 00:12:31,335
You call your retired detective back and at least get her to confirm her case details.

165
00:12:31,418 --> 00:12:33,837
We need something on the record
from the police.

166
00:12:36,548 --> 00:12:38,926
[pedestrian] Meet us down by the pier.
See you there.

167
00:12:41,094 --> 00:12:42,346
It should be right here.

168
00:12:47,601 --> 00:12:48,936
What's this guy's deal?

169
00:12:52,147 --> 00:12:53,273
[door buzzes]

170
00:12:58,445 --> 00:12:59,863
[Warren] Come on straight back.

171
00:13:05,786 --> 00:13:07,538
Hi. Did Dan send you?

172
00:13:08,121 --> 00:13:10,934
- Yeah. We're with the Sun-Times.
- [Warren] That's the outputs over there.

173
00:13:10,958 --> 00:13:13,544
Everything I could isolate
off the noise floor is in the report.

174
00:13:16,922 --> 00:13:18,632
This is all of them? Thank you.

175
00:13:26,139 --> 00:13:28,809
All right. This one, uh,
with the background noises.

176
00:13:28,892 --> 00:13:31,395
- Would you mind cuing it up?
- Sure. I charge by the hour.

177
00:13:32,396 --> 00:13:33,480
Dan will cover it.

178
00:13:34,231 --> 00:13:35,232
Yeah. Thank you.

179
00:13:40,779 --> 00:13:44,950
- Quality's rough.
- [whirring] She was using her answering machine to record the calls.

180
00:13:48,704 --> 00:13:51,373
[automated voice] August 13th. 3:03 p.m.

181
00:13:51,957 --> 00:13:52,958
[Julia] Hello?

182
00:13:53,709 --> 00:13:55,949
[Warren] For the first couple of days,
it's all hang-ups.

183
00:13:56,003 --> 00:14:00,799
- [Julia] Hello?
- [siren wailing over tape] - Hear that? - Yeah. Tornado warning.

184
00:14:00,883 --> 00:14:02,509
Sound like air-raid sirens.

185
00:14:03,385 --> 00:14:04,511
[Warren] Where'd you serve?

186
00:14:05,262 --> 00:14:07,055
1st Cav. A Shau Valley.

187
00:14:09,183 --> 00:14:12,060
Uh, 1990. That must've been
the Plainfield tornado, right?

188
00:14:13,020 --> 00:14:14,860
You were real pissed
when I went to shoot that.

189
00:14:18,275 --> 00:14:20,819
Those tornado warnings,
they were all over the city.

190
00:14:20,903 --> 00:14:22,362
So, he could've been anywhere.

191
00:14:22,446 --> 00:14:23,447
I pulled what was there.

192
00:14:23,530 --> 00:14:24,907
[Julia] Hello?

193
00:14:25,407 --> 00:14:26,533
I called the police.

194
00:14:28,452 --> 00:14:30,829
[Harper] They'll be there in 18 minutes.

195
00:14:31,330 --> 00:14:32,456
[Julia] They're here now.

196
00:14:32,539 --> 00:14:34,625
- [Harper scoffs] No, they're not.
- Is that him?

197
00:14:35,918 --> 00:14:41,590
- Yeah.
- You see, I'm, uh… I'm already with you when they arrive.

198
00:14:41,673 --> 00:14:43,675
Can you cue up the first time he called?

199
00:14:44,468 --> 00:14:46,929
- [Warren] Sure.
- I'm with you every moment. I'm...

200
00:14:49,264 --> 00:14:50,265
[Julia echoes] Hello?

201
00:14:50,974 --> 00:14:55,479
[echoing] Hello? Why are you doing this?

202
00:14:55,562 --> 00:14:58,041
- [Harper breathing heavily]
- [echoing] How are you doing this?

203
00:14:58,065 --> 00:14:59,816
[Warren]
Just a lot of breathing after that.

204
00:14:59,900 --> 00:15:02,319
- What's with the echo?
- [Warren] Probably the line.

205
00:15:02,402 --> 00:15:05,906
You get that if there's network hops.
Water damage in the wiring can do it too.

206
00:15:06,406 --> 00:15:08,200
Here, I'll pull the two apart for you.

207
00:15:09,409 --> 00:15:10,661
Here's the first one.

208
00:15:12,913 --> 00:15:14,831
[Julia] Hello? Hello?

209
00:15:16,083 --> 00:15:17,376
Why are you doing this?

210
00:15:18,293 --> 00:15:19,878
How are you doing this?

211
00:15:22,172 --> 00:15:23,423
[tape clicks]

212
00:15:23,507 --> 00:15:24,675
Now, here's the echo.

213
00:15:25,843 --> 00:15:27,928
[Julia] Hello? Hello?

214
00:15:28,762 --> 00:15:31,723
Why are you doing this?
How are you doing this?

215
00:15:33,350 --> 00:15:35,477
It's different.
She doesn't sound the same.

216
00:15:35,561 --> 00:15:37,563
The first one's filtered
like it was recorded.

217
00:15:37,646 --> 00:15:39,231
The second is her voice on the line.

218
00:15:40,899 --> 00:15:44,862
He's playing a recording of her
before she even says the words?

219
00:15:45,362 --> 00:15:47,489
[Warren]
Let me play them again side by side.

220
00:15:49,950 --> 00:15:52,661
[Julia echoes] Hello? Hello?

221
00:15:53,328 --> 00:15:55,497
[echoing] Why are you doing this?

222
00:15:56,123 --> 00:15:57,875
[echoing] How are you doing this?

223
00:16:02,796 --> 00:16:04,298
[tools clattering]

224
00:16:05,716 --> 00:16:07,342
[coughs, sniffs]

225
00:16:11,096 --> 00:16:12,222
[objects thump]

226
00:16:17,811 --> 00:16:19,229
[glass shatters]

227
00:16:26,945 --> 00:16:28,155
[door opens]

228
00:16:45,756 --> 00:16:47,257
[grunts, yelps]

229
00:16:49,551 --> 00:16:50,552
[grunts]

230
00:16:52,554 --> 00:16:54,848
[struggling] What the fuck? What the...

231
00:16:54,932 --> 00:16:56,099
Take it! Take whatever!

232
00:16:56,683 --> 00:16:58,810
- Why are you here?
- I live here. What the fuck?

233
00:16:58,894 --> 00:17:00,437
Why are you here?

234
00:17:01,188 --> 00:17:02,731
I live here.

235
00:17:02,814 --> 00:17:04,775
What do you want? Just take whatever.

236
00:17:07,444 --> 00:17:08,904
- Where's Sharon?
- Who?

237
00:17:10,155 --> 00:17:11,716
- [whimpers]
- How long have you lived here?

238
00:17:11,740 --> 00:17:13,200
- What?
- How long?

239
00:17:13,282 --> 00:17:14,826
I don't know, like, four years.

240
00:17:14,910 --> 00:17:18,454
No, Sharon lives here.
I know she does. Where is she?

241
00:17:19,665 --> 00:17:24,044
I don't know. I don't know any Sharon!
I don't know where she is.

242
00:17:24,127 --> 00:17:25,796
- [whimpers]
- Who lived here before you?

243
00:17:25,878 --> 00:17:28,632
- What? [groans]
- Before you, who lived here?

244
00:17:28,715 --> 00:17:31,760
Some old dude. Still get his mail.
There's no place to send it.

245
00:17:31,844 --> 00:17:33,154
I think he's dead. Do you want it?

246
00:17:33,178 --> 00:17:34,429
- Shut up!
- [shouts]

247
00:17:34,513 --> 00:17:36,515
[whimpering]

248
00:17:52,072 --> 00:17:53,657
That breaks, and you're dead.

249
00:17:53,740 --> 00:17:55,325
[crying]

250
00:17:58,453 --> 00:18:00,956
[breathing shakily]

251
00:18:30,903 --> 00:18:31,904
Hey, you good?

252
00:18:32,779 --> 00:18:34,156
You heard that, right?

253
00:18:34,239 --> 00:18:35,449
I don't know what I heard.

254
00:18:36,366 --> 00:18:40,370
He knew what she was gonna say.
He recorded her before she even said it.

255
00:18:41,872 --> 00:18:44,249
Are you sure you never got
any calls like that?

256
00:18:47,753 --> 00:18:49,087
I didn't know what it was.

257
00:18:51,006 --> 00:18:52,841
I had just started working at the Tribune.

258
00:18:53,800 --> 00:18:55,802
Wasn't that like years before
what happened to you?

259
00:18:55,886 --> 00:18:56,887
Yeah.

260
00:18:56,970 --> 00:19:00,682
It was just a few hang-ups
at that office and… Then what?

261
00:19:02,976 --> 00:19:04,019
[laughs]

262
00:19:06,563 --> 00:19:09,483
- You don't have to do this. [sighs]
- Do what?

263
00:19:09,566 --> 00:19:10,984
Ask me questions. And it's...

264
00:19:11,068 --> 00:19:14,154
What the fuck are you talking about?
I should be your first stop.

265
00:19:14,238 --> 00:19:17,198
I don't wanna have to be in a meeting
to find out what's going on with you.

266
00:19:18,408 --> 00:19:19,826
Were there any other times?

267
00:19:25,457 --> 00:19:27,960
[Marcus]
This is not what I had in my head.

268
00:19:29,461 --> 00:19:30,587
[Kirby] What'd you expect?

269
00:19:31,255 --> 00:19:33,757
[Marcus] I mean, you said this place
was like a second home.

270
00:19:34,508 --> 00:19:36,051
It's a pretty big one. [chuckles]

271
00:19:36,593 --> 00:19:38,512
Yeah, it feels smaller with the crowds.

272
00:19:39,012 --> 00:19:40,973
Your mom would
just let you wander around here?

273
00:19:41,557 --> 00:19:49,773
Well, she worked the 2:00 a.m. show
three times a week, and she couldn't pay for a babysitter. So, this was it.

274
00:20:04,371 --> 00:20:06,248
[Marcus] Hey, what are you looking for?

275
00:20:10,627 --> 00:20:11,628
Kirby?

276
00:20:13,130 --> 00:20:14,464
[keys jingle]

277
00:20:14,548 --> 00:20:15,841
What are you doing?

278
00:20:15,924 --> 00:20:18,010
It should still be here.
Everything else is.

279
00:20:19,803 --> 00:20:22,806
[guitar playing]

280
00:20:23,932 --> 00:20:26,602
[vocalizing]

281
00:20:26,685 --> 00:20:28,288
[guitarist]
I don't understand what it adds.

282
00:20:28,312 --> 00:20:30,230
It adds texture.

283
00:20:30,314 --> 00:20:32,608
Jesus, this is not some garage shit.

284
00:20:32,691 --> 00:20:33,692
[Sharon] Hey, Mom.

285
00:20:33,775 --> 00:20:34,776
- Hey, Sharon.
- Hey.

286
00:20:34,860 --> 00:20:37,130
[Rachel clears throat] My throat is dry.
Why is it so cold in here?

287
00:20:37,154 --> 00:20:39,072
You wanted a clean demo. No crowds.

288
00:20:41,033 --> 00:20:43,285
[clears throat]
I'm gonna blow a vocal cord.

289
00:20:44,077 --> 00:20:46,205
Aw, thanks, baby. [sighs]

290
00:20:49,374 --> 00:20:51,001
Which one of you did that?

291
00:20:54,922 --> 00:20:56,548
And they're gone like this song.

292
00:20:57,424 --> 00:20:58,425
[Rachel] What?

293
00:20:58,509 --> 00:21:01,345
Leonard Cohen.
I play it for you all the time.

294
00:21:02,846 --> 00:21:05,224
[sighs] Maybe you have a secret admirer.

295
00:21:05,724 --> 00:21:07,100
Don't let it go to your head.

296
00:21:07,601 --> 00:21:09,144
What's got you all worked up?

297
00:21:10,020 --> 00:21:14,107
[sighs] Tommy got a tape to Vee
over at Touch and Go.

298
00:21:15,067 --> 00:21:17,277
So, I mean, they didn't put up a lot for...

299
00:21:17,361 --> 00:21:20,864
But they're gonna cover a promo
and distro and...

300
00:21:21,823 --> 00:21:23,367
Yeah, it'll be 50-50 split.

301
00:21:23,450 --> 00:21:26,203
Ah, it's gonna be good.
Do you want me to stay?

302
00:21:27,246 --> 00:21:30,541
Well, I wouldn't want to, uh, disrupt
your office drone routine.

303
00:21:30,624 --> 00:21:31,625
Give it a fucking rest.

304
00:21:31,708 --> 00:21:34,253
- [guitar feedback]
- [Rachel groans] It's a newspaper. It's...

305
00:21:34,336 --> 00:21:35,796
[Rachel] This guy.

306
00:21:35,879 --> 00:21:40,300
He's played for half his life,
and he still can't work a delay pedal!

307
00:21:41,260 --> 00:21:44,180
- [guitarist] You think you can do better?
- [Rachel] Yeah, I think I can.

308
00:21:44,471 --> 00:21:45,639
And, uh, Sharon...

309
00:21:45,722 --> 00:21:50,227
Sharon, I know that... that climbing
the corporate ladder is a lot, but...

310
00:21:50,310 --> 00:21:52,062
Why do I fucking sound like
I'm in Siberia?

311
00:21:52,145 --> 00:21:53,355
You said, "Monster reverb."

312
00:21:53,438 --> 00:21:55,941
[Rachel] Yeah, monster.
Like big, not like inaudible.

313
00:21:56,024 --> 00:21:58,610
- [phone rings]
- Will you get it? Tell them it's closed.

314
00:21:59,194 --> 00:22:01,714
- That's not my job anymore.
- Well, I am trying to do my job...

315
00:22:01,780 --> 00:22:04,780
You can either be farther back in the mix
and delayed or up close and crisp.

316
00:22:04,825 --> 00:22:07,244
- Just fucking turn me off.
- [guitarist] You can't be both.

317
00:22:07,327 --> 00:22:09,222
- [Rachel] Turn me the fuck off.
- [guitarist] You can't do both.

318
00:22:09,246 --> 00:22:20,382
- Hey. Sid's. We're closed right now.
- [music blaring on phone] - Jesus. Turn your music down. - [musical feedback on phone] - [guitar feedback on phone] - [Rachel] What the fuck?

319
00:22:20,883 --> 00:22:22,342
[Rachel] What the fuck?

320
00:22:22,426 --> 00:22:25,095
[musicians playing rock song]

321
00:22:25,179 --> 00:22:27,181
[Rachel] Yeah. Yes, yes. More. More!

322
00:22:28,265 --> 00:22:29,266
[Rachel] What?

323
00:22:31,977 --> 00:22:33,121
[guitarist] I fucking told you.

324
00:22:33,145 --> 00:22:35,314
[Rachel] Sharon! Get over here.

325
00:22:35,397 --> 00:22:36,982
[guitarist] I fucking told you.

326
00:22:37,065 --> 00:22:40,319
Sharon! Get over here.
Bring me another tube.

327
00:22:42,529 --> 00:22:44,531
[breathing heavily]

328
00:22:47,951 --> 00:22:49,786
[key scraping]

329
00:22:55,751 --> 00:22:59,546
I was just like Julia. He was here.

330
00:23:03,133 --> 00:23:06,136
[Marcus] When you first got the calls,
you never told Rachel?

331
00:23:07,888 --> 00:23:11,433
What would I have said?
It would've seemed crazy.

332
00:23:12,017 --> 00:23:16,396
And then the calls just stopped.
But he didn't. He just waited.

333
00:23:19,816 --> 00:23:21,401
I just never realized it was him.

334
00:23:26,406 --> 00:23:28,134
[interviewee]
Catherine wouldn't go out on her own.

335
00:23:28,158 --> 00:23:29,952
I always had to knock on doors with her.

336
00:23:30,035 --> 00:23:33,247
We tried to hit 20 doors an hour.
We covered a lot of ground.

337
00:23:33,747 --> 00:23:35,475
This was Mayor Washington's
first campaign, right?

338
00:23:35,499 --> 00:23:36,333
Yeah.

339
00:23:36,416 --> 00:23:39,419
[Dan] Was she political?
She ever volunteer for any campaigns?

340
00:23:40,587 --> 00:23:42,840
No. Uh, Anne cared about other things.

341
00:23:42,923 --> 00:23:45,259
About her family.
About me. People around her.

342
00:23:45,884 --> 00:23:47,761
[union rep]
Margot went with this nice kid.

343
00:23:47,845 --> 00:23:49,471
Uh, he was in Carpenters Local 13.

344
00:23:49,555 --> 00:23:51,557
She didn't live alone?

345
00:23:51,640 --> 00:23:54,393
No. It would have been
them two and a little girl.

346
00:23:54,476 --> 00:23:57,062
Uh, Bonnie, Betty, something like that.

347
00:23:57,145 --> 00:23:58,355
She had a daughter?

348
00:23:58,438 --> 00:24:00,357
Karen never talked about kids.

349
00:24:01,066 --> 00:24:05,487
She was studying music
but switched to nursing when I got sick.

350
00:24:06,446 --> 00:24:11,827
She... She worked at, um,
Provident Hospital?

351
00:24:11,910 --> 00:24:12,911
Yeah.

352
00:24:12,995 --> 00:24:16,999
She got her real estate license in 1985?

353
00:24:17,082 --> 00:24:18,458
Yeah, just before she got killed.

354
00:24:18,542 --> 00:24:20,436
Yeah. She ever show any places
on the South Side?

355
00:24:20,460 --> 00:24:21,604
No. We were in Andersonville.

356
00:24:21,628 --> 00:24:23,797
We spent the entire summer canvassing
the South Side.

357
00:24:23,881 --> 00:24:28,177
Which neighborhoods?
Maybe Englewood? Bronzeville?

358
00:24:28,260 --> 00:24:29,845
No, just Woodlawn.

359
00:24:29,928 --> 00:24:33,849
Between your care and the hospital, she must not have had time for much else, right?

360
00:24:33,932 --> 00:24:36,768
She didn't mind. She liked being home.

361
00:24:36,852 --> 00:24:38,729
They weren't married. I remember that.

362
00:24:38,812 --> 00:24:40,814
Which was a much bigger deal back then.

363
00:24:40,898 --> 00:24:43,650
Any of these other women volunteer for it?

364
00:24:43,734 --> 00:24:45,753
- I'm sorry. I don't know any of them.
- I don't know.

365
00:24:45,777 --> 00:24:48,864
[Dan] Maybe she met them at church,
a bar, club?

366
00:24:49,990 --> 00:24:52,201
[Dan] Did she know any of these women?

367
00:24:52,284 --> 00:24:53,553
…involved with any of these women?

368
00:24:53,577 --> 00:24:54,828
Any of these women?

369
00:24:54,912 --> 00:24:56,038
Know any of these women?

370
00:24:56,622 --> 00:24:58,982
[interviewee 2] I don't understand.
What's your story about?

371
00:25:13,555 --> 00:25:15,474
You lived with Summer over in Kenwood?

372
00:25:16,350 --> 00:25:18,727
[roommate] You mean,
how did I climb from there to here?

373
00:25:19,228 --> 00:25:21,897
[chuckles]
I'm a libel attorney, and this is America.

374
00:25:21,980 --> 00:25:22,981
[chuckles]

375
00:25:23,857 --> 00:25:25,901
Is that how you guys met? Law school?

376
00:25:25,984 --> 00:25:29,071
[scoffs] We met partying. We were 20.

377
00:25:29,154 --> 00:25:33,534
[sighs] Must have been hard
losing your roommate at that age.

378
00:25:34,243 --> 00:25:36,870
Roommate? [scoffs]
Is that what the police told you?

379
00:25:38,830 --> 00:25:39,915
[chuckles]

380
00:25:40,666 --> 00:25:42,546
- They miss everything, right?
- [chuckles] Mmm.

381
00:25:44,461 --> 00:25:49,758
Did either of you come across
any of these women?

382
00:25:52,302 --> 00:25:54,596
[clicks tongue]
I don't know. Maybe she did.

383
00:25:55,097 --> 00:25:57,599
Summer changed a lot
right before it happened.

384
00:25:59,017 --> 00:26:00,227
Like how?

385
00:26:00,310 --> 00:26:02,271
She got quiet, distant.

386
00:26:02,855 --> 00:26:04,022
Do you know why?

387
00:26:04,773 --> 00:26:09,278
I thought she was seeing someone else,
but I never asked.

388
00:26:09,361 --> 00:26:12,364
I figured she'd break up with me
if I pushed too hard.

389
00:26:13,115 --> 00:26:18,245
But she never said anything,
like a name or, uh, somewhere she went?

390
00:26:18,328 --> 00:26:20,330
- Something like that.
- Mm-mmm.

391
00:26:21,415 --> 00:26:23,667
I kept thinking what we did wrong.

392
00:26:23,750 --> 00:26:26,170
Went to the wrong parties,
knew the wrong people.

393
00:26:26,253 --> 00:26:27,504
There were plenty.

394
00:26:27,588 --> 00:26:30,632
But it still never made any fucking sense.

395
00:26:34,303 --> 00:26:35,304
I kept some photos.

396
00:26:36,388 --> 00:26:38,724
You can see for yourself
how beautiful she was.

397
00:26:48,650 --> 00:26:51,320
We spent a couple of summers in Saugatuck.

398
00:26:52,446 --> 00:26:57,701
Yeah. Took a few watercolor classes.
Puttered around.

399
00:26:57,784 --> 00:26:59,661
That was more her speed than Kenwood.

400
00:27:01,705 --> 00:27:02,915
- You mind if I…
- Oh.

401
00:27:12,299 --> 00:27:14,218
Her grandmother gave her that
for some birthday.

402
00:27:19,723 --> 00:27:21,183
- What's wrong?
- Give me a sec.

403
00:27:33,779 --> 00:27:34,905
Was this Summer's?

404
00:27:36,782 --> 00:27:39,826
Yeah. Yeah, it was a part of the set.
Where's this from?

405
00:27:40,994 --> 00:27:43,872
Did you know this woman? Did Summer?

406
00:27:45,290 --> 00:27:47,459
I don't think so. Why?

407
00:27:52,047 --> 00:27:54,883
[sighs] You gonna tell Dan about Sid's?

408
00:27:56,051 --> 00:27:57,052
You don't think I should?

409
00:27:58,220 --> 00:28:01,139
No, I don't. It'll end up
in his fourth graph as filler.

410
00:28:02,891 --> 00:28:04,691
[Marcus] Hey, hey.
You pulling an all-nighter?

411
00:28:04,726 --> 00:28:06,486
Yeah, we're breaking
Dan's cold case murders.

412
00:28:07,020 --> 00:28:08,897
- Tonight?
- [Lakshmi] Kirby, wait.

413
00:28:09,690 --> 00:28:11,525
Fuck. I need her to pull
like a hundred clips.

414
00:28:11,608 --> 00:28:13,485
[Kirby]
How are you going to press already?

415
00:28:13,569 --> 00:28:16,780
Where you been?
You were gone, like, six hours. Come here.

416
00:28:20,868 --> 00:28:27,374
So, this… belonged to Summer Francis.

417
00:28:30,502 --> 00:28:33,630
And this was found with Margot Zelle.

418
00:28:41,889 --> 00:28:44,308
He took the mirror from one
and left it in another.

419
00:28:44,808 --> 00:28:47,352
These women don't know each other.

420
00:28:47,978 --> 00:28:50,022
They don't have anything in common.

421
00:28:50,105 --> 00:28:51,773
He is the one connecting them.

422
00:28:54,902 --> 00:28:57,196
Willie Rose was left with a pin.

423
00:29:00,908 --> 00:29:06,079
Let me see. It's a... It's a nurse's pin.

424
00:29:07,956 --> 00:29:09,374
Karen worked at Provident Hospital.

425
00:29:09,958 --> 00:29:12,044
He took it from Karen,
left it with Willie.

426
00:29:14,254 --> 00:29:15,464
What was found in Karen?

427
00:29:18,967 --> 00:29:21,261
Catherine Moore.
Whose campaign did she work on?

428
00:29:22,179 --> 00:29:23,597
Harold Washington. [chuckles]

429
00:29:24,640 --> 00:29:26,433
- Hey, Jimmy.
- Yeah?

430
00:29:26,517 --> 00:29:28,352
What was
Harold Washington's campaign slogan?

431
00:29:28,435 --> 00:29:30,687
Uh, "The silence is deafening."

432
00:29:32,272 --> 00:29:33,273
[Kirby sighs]

433
00:29:35,317 --> 00:29:37,402
This, this is Catherine's.

434
00:29:37,986 --> 00:29:39,947
Julia, Julia. She was a social worker.

435
00:29:40,030 --> 00:29:43,116
Were there any other kind of IDs
or anything like that?

436
00:29:43,617 --> 00:29:44,701
Catholic, right?

437
00:29:45,744 --> 00:29:47,621
Safe guess. She was from Jefferson Park.

438
00:29:47,704 --> 00:29:50,499
The devotional card could be hers.
Found with Anne Lower.

439
00:29:54,211 --> 00:29:58,298
Anne was killed in '85 and Julia in '90.

440
00:29:58,382 --> 00:30:01,385
So, he must have taken the card
from Anne by then.

441
00:30:01,468 --> 00:30:04,346
But he doesn't kill Julia
for another five years.

442
00:30:06,431 --> 00:30:08,016
What is he doing all that time?

443
00:30:09,226 --> 00:30:11,979
[Kirby] He watched us,
sometimes for years.

444
00:30:12,062 --> 00:30:14,082
We didn't know he was there,
not until he wanted us to.

445
00:30:14,106 --> 00:30:15,583
[Abby] How did no one catch on to him?

446
00:30:15,607 --> 00:30:18,777
'Cause he picked random victims.
He moved around. He kept his distance.

447
00:30:18,861 --> 00:30:21,947
He didn't, though.
He got close. He knew all about us.

448
00:30:22,531 --> 00:30:24,950
- Knew what?
- We need to run with what we have.

449
00:30:25,033 --> 00:30:27,828
We should start with Julia.
She's been our coverage so far.

450
00:30:32,416 --> 00:30:36,128
You should lead with me.
I'll give you a firsthand account.

451
00:30:36,211 --> 00:30:39,006
You can have my police report,
hospital photos, whatever you need.

452
00:30:41,717 --> 00:30:44,720
If we include all that,
we will not be able to hide who you are.

453
00:30:44,803 --> 00:30:45,804
I know.

454
00:30:48,140 --> 00:30:51,894
You sure?
We can make do with what we have.

455
00:30:52,561 --> 00:30:57,024
I'm the better story.
That's what I want for this.

456
00:30:58,901 --> 00:31:00,402
Pawel's hearing is wrapping up.

457
00:31:00,485 --> 00:31:03,488
We need to make a show of offering
the police a chance to comment.

458
00:31:11,121 --> 00:31:12,414
[Abby] Let's go, Dan.

459
00:31:29,223 --> 00:31:33,060
Let's go. We gotta get there
before the press conference.

460
00:31:39,316 --> 00:31:40,317
[Dan] What is it?

461
00:31:40,400 --> 00:31:42,819
The key. From the planetarium.

462
00:31:42,903 --> 00:31:45,463
I should talk to the woman who lost it.
Let her know all of this.

463
00:31:45,489 --> 00:31:46,823
You still think she's connected?

464
00:31:47,699 --> 00:31:49,535
He took her key. She has to be.

465
00:31:52,621 --> 00:31:56,124
Take this in case she wants to see it.

466
00:31:56,208 --> 00:31:57,209
Okay.

467
00:32:26,697 --> 00:32:28,866
[call box rings]

468
00:32:28,949 --> 00:32:29,950
[Jinny] Hello?

469
00:32:30,450 --> 00:32:33,412
Hi, I'm Kirby Mazrachi.
I asked you about the key chain you lost.

470
00:32:33,912 --> 00:32:35,873
Okay. Why are you here?

471
00:32:37,291 --> 00:32:40,586
Your key, it was found
on a woman who was murdered.

472
00:32:41,587 --> 00:32:43,881
The photo I showed you was
from a crime scene.

473
00:32:47,050 --> 00:32:48,760
[door buzzes]

474
00:32:49,970 --> 00:32:53,182
[footsteps]

475
00:33:00,397 --> 00:33:01,899
Thank you for letting me up.

476
00:33:10,616 --> 00:33:14,536
I've never had any hang-ups,
no weird calls, nothing like that.

477
00:33:14,620 --> 00:33:17,915
- Not even years ago?
- Never. None of this is happening to me.

478
00:33:18,415 --> 00:33:20,292
[clicks tongue] Try to really think back.

479
00:33:20,375 --> 00:33:23,712
I mean, if there was some heavy breather
outside my window, I would know.

480
00:33:24,296 --> 00:33:27,633
I didn't. I was assaulted by the same man.

481
00:33:29,968 --> 00:33:30,969
Oh.

482
00:33:33,722 --> 00:33:34,973
I'm really sorry.

483
00:33:35,766 --> 00:33:39,019
He watched me for years. I had no idea.

484
00:33:39,811 --> 00:33:41,522
Well, I'm not you.

485
00:33:42,189 --> 00:33:46,151
Then why was your key
left inside a dead woman?

486
00:33:47,986 --> 00:33:50,614
But you said this photo was
from 20 years ago.

487
00:33:53,283 --> 00:33:56,245
[sighs] You're sure those were only made
last year?

488
00:33:56,328 --> 00:33:59,831
Yes. Hubble returned
its first picture of Jupiter.

489
00:33:59,915 --> 00:34:00,958
We did a whole exhibit.

490
00:34:01,917 --> 00:34:04,086
[sighs] Look, I don't know
what you want me to do.

491
00:34:04,169 --> 00:34:09,507
Stay with friends, family.
Don't go out on your own. I carry a knife.

492
00:34:11,844 --> 00:34:15,472
Um. Sor... I'm sorry.
I-I have to get going.

493
00:34:16,056 --> 00:34:17,933
I, um... [clicks tongue]

494
00:34:18,016 --> 00:34:20,185
- I-I'm covering the midnight show, so...
- Sure.

495
00:34:21,395 --> 00:34:22,728
[thunder rumbles]

496
00:34:31,029 --> 00:34:34,032
[Jinny sighs]
We won't be able to see shit tonight.

497
00:34:34,699 --> 00:34:36,827
You should really figure out
how you lost that key.

498
00:34:39,121 --> 00:34:40,121
Still have mine.

499
00:34:43,250 --> 00:34:47,462
He left something with those other women.
What about you?

500
00:34:48,630 --> 00:34:49,672
A matchbook.

501
00:34:51,216 --> 00:34:52,217
Whose was it?

502
00:34:53,510 --> 00:34:54,636
I don't know.

503
00:34:55,469 --> 00:34:57,264
It's from some bar
that doesn't even exist.

504
00:34:59,892 --> 00:35:02,452
Just because something hasn't happened yet
doesn't mean it won't.

505
00:35:02,811 --> 00:35:05,856
It always takes looking at something
a few times before it makes sense.

506
00:35:05,939 --> 00:35:08,901
If you figure it all out, give me a call.

507
00:35:15,991 --> 00:35:18,076
[thunder rumbles]

508
00:35:23,790 --> 00:35:25,990
- [Jinny] Can I grab the red one?
- [vendor] Five bucks.

509
00:36:30,482 --> 00:36:31,650
[door rattles]

510
00:36:43,996 --> 00:36:45,497
[bangs on door]

511
00:36:45,581 --> 00:36:47,583
[metal clinks]

512
00:37:50,979 --> 00:37:52,481
[Harper] You don't look right.

513
00:37:56,485 --> 00:37:57,778
What's wrong with your hair?

514
00:37:59,863 --> 00:38:04,535
Stopped by your place.
Somebody else was living there.

515
00:38:06,453 --> 00:38:08,173
- I don't know who y...
- When did you move?

516
00:38:11,542 --> 00:38:13,085
[Kirby breathing heavily]

517
00:38:13,710 --> 00:38:14,962
You didn't know Jinny.

518
00:38:16,255 --> 00:38:18,382
I know you didn't.
None of you knew each other.

519
00:38:20,717 --> 00:38:21,927
How did you find her?

520
00:38:23,303 --> 00:38:24,513
Or did she find you?

521
00:38:25,514 --> 00:38:28,058
Yeah, maybe that's it,
'cause she's smarter than you are.

522
00:38:28,725 --> 00:38:30,727
Stop. Fucking stop.

523
00:38:30,811 --> 00:38:34,648
You look different.
I don't like you like this.

524
00:38:42,990 --> 00:38:47,578
You remember me… from Eldridge Street?

525
00:38:51,206 --> 00:38:52,875
You gave me the horse.

526
00:38:53,458 --> 00:38:56,420
The Pegasus. It had wings.
Horses are just hooves and tails.

527
00:38:57,212 --> 00:38:58,213
I...

528
00:39:01,133 --> 00:39:02,551
You look the same.

529
00:39:04,595 --> 00:39:05,971
And you look different.

530
00:39:08,932 --> 00:39:10,201
- Nothing like I left you.
- [gasps]

531
00:39:10,225 --> 00:39:11,518
[yelps, grunts]

532
00:39:11,602 --> 00:39:14,479
- I killed you. You shouldn't be here.
- [Kirby breathing heavily]

533
00:39:16,356 --> 00:39:17,691
[Harper yells]

534
00:39:17,774 --> 00:39:18,775
[Kirby grunts]

535
00:39:20,360 --> 00:39:24,156
- [Harper grunts]
- [Kirby grunts] - [choking] - Did you do that?

536
00:39:24,239 --> 00:39:25,657
[Kirby coughs, pants]

537
00:39:27,868 --> 00:39:34,333
- [Harper grunts]
- [Kirby gasps] This can't be happening. This can't be happening here.

538
00:39:42,132 --> 00:39:43,967
- Who are you?
- [choking continues]

539
00:39:45,886 --> 00:39:46,929
[Harper grunts]
